ProjectTitle: FEASIBILITY OF COPPER SLAG-FLY ASH-SOIL MIX AS A ROAD CONSTRUCTION MATERIAL

AdditionalInfo.StudentNames: PURAM ABHINAY
AdditionalInfo.Abtract: The use of waste materials in the road construction industry is gradually gaining significance in India, considering disposal and environmental problems and the gradual depletion of natural resources.  The potential use of these materials in road construction was studied initially by evaluating the materials for their physical and chemical characteristics. The waste materials were mixed with local soils in the range of 25% to 75%, and their geotechnical characteristics were investigated. The feasibility of using these mixes in the base course of road pavement was investigated by adopting stabilization techniques. The potential of copper slag as a replacement for fine aggregates in bituminous mixes was also investigated. It was concluded that a mixture of copper slag, fly ash, and soil has the potential for use in embankment, subbase, base, and wearing courses of road pavement. The results of laboratory tests and typical technical design specifications indicating the utility of copper slag, fly ash, and soil in different layers of road pavement are discussed.

Types of deteriorating are rutting ,fatigue and low temperature cracking. To prevent these all distresses different types of polymer modifiers have been utilized. In this paper ,they use of blended synthetic fibers as a low cost modifier in bituminous pavement mix was found to be effective in improving performance compared to other modifiers. In this study, a mixture of polypropylene and aramid fibers was introduced to evaluate the performance characteristics of a bituminous mixture. The laboratory experimental program included indirect tensile strength tests, wet indirect tensile strength after water and MIST (Moisture Induced Sensitivity Test) conditioned, dynamic creep and resilient modulus at different temperatures. This paper reports of the reduction of thickness of pavement also cost analysis with the addition of fibers and resulting properties.

ProjectTitle: THE PERFORMANCE OF AGED ASPHALT MATERIALS REJUVENATED WITH WASTE ENGINE OIL

AdditionalInfo.StudentNames: MANTHRIPRAGADA ADITYA RAJ
AdditionalInfo.Abtract: Waste engine oil from automobiles has been shown to improve asphalt binder when applied in small quantities, with the added advantage of being a waste product itself. Using waste engine oil as a chemical additive to restore the properties of RAP uses one waste material to increase the recyclability of another, which is environmentally and socially desirable.PG 58-28 neat, virgin binder was blended with reclaimed asphalt binder (RAB) and waste engine oil. The blends were then tested to study the interactions between RAB and waste engine oil. Using Fourier-Transform Infrared Spectroscopy (FT-IR), the differences in the samples were compared using the structural indices associated with asphalt binder aging. This testing revealed a decrease in the two aging indices of the blended asphalt binder, indicating that waste engine oil has the ability to chemically restore aged asphalt binder.Asphalt mixture testing was then performed with mixtures of virgin asphalt, virgin binder, RAP and waste engine oil, in quantities similar to the binder testing, to see if the rejuvenation shown in FT-IR led to an improvement in the performance of the pavement specimens. After specimens were created, testing for freeze thaw durability, and rutting susceptibility was conducted. The results of the mixture testing failed to show an improvement of the freeze thaw durability or rutting susceptibility of specimens created with RAP and waste engine oil when compared to mixtures containing only new materials.

ProjectTitle: IMPLEMENTATION OF SIX SIGMA CONCEPTS IN INDUSTRY LEADING TO OPTIMIZATION OF OUTPUT PARAMETERS

AdditionalInfo.StudentNames: PULUMADDI SAFALA
AdditionalInfo.Abtract:
Six Sigma aims at a very high quality level. It sets target to achieve 3.4 defects per million opportunities(DPMO).It aims at controlling process variations very significantly. When organizations go from 3 sigma to 6 sigma , the cost of quality could go down to less than 1% of sales. This is clearly a profit for the organization. Six Sigma aims at controlling the defects to the minimum. It aims at nearly eliminating the wastes and rework and thereby improving the profit margin. In the organization chosen,  the  six sigma methodology is carried out as below 1.Measurement  of current  process  performance 2.Improvement  of performance through experimentation 3. Achieving six sigma level through continuous measurements, analysis and improvement.  Basically, six sigma aims at reduction of the deviation from the mean.
Project students are advised to select  one of the following industries to implement the  six sigma  methodology
1. A  manufacturing  or a process industry 
2. A business industry  like a bank
3. A  healthcare  industry like a multispecialty  hospital
4. A service industry like an educational institute like VNRVJIET    etc.
Generally, two methodologies are used for the implementation of six sigma. They are
1. DMAIC   (Define, Measure, Analyze, Improve, Control) for existing products/services
2. DMADV (Define, Measure, Analyze, Design, Verify) for new products/services.

ProjectTitle: REDUCTION OF INDUCTIVE LOSSES IN ELECTRIC VEHICLE WIRELESS CHARGING THROUGH RESONANT COUPLING

G. RAVI SAI HEMANTH (20071A2407)
AdditionalInfo.Abtract:
Wireless electric vehicle charging (WEVC) systems have emerged as a promising solution to
address the limitations of conventional wired charging infrastructure for electric vehicles (EVs).
These systems offer the convenience of charging electric vehicles without the need for physical
plug-in connections, reducing user involvement and automating the charging process. Wireless
charging systems typically experience lower efficiency compared to wired charging due to
energy losses during power transfer. The use of resonant coupling can improve efficiency, but
some power is still lost as heat during transmission, leading to slightly longer charging times
and potential energy waste. Where this issue can be resolved with resonant wireless power
transfer (RWPT). Resonant wireless electric vehicle charging is an innovative technology that
offers a promising solution to the challenges of conventional wired charging systems for electric
vehicles. Wireless electric vehicle charging utilizes the principle of electromagnetic resonance
to transfer electrical energy between a charging station (base station) and an electric vehicle
equipped with a receiving unit. The system involves two coils, one integrated into the charging
station and the other installed on the underside of the electric vehicle. These coils are tuned to
resonate at the same frequency, allowing efficient power transfer over short distances without
physical contact. Resonant wireless charging offers increased efficiency over conventional
inductive charging. Resonating couple is a new area of research, which is achieved by a
frequency oscillator. But, the same resonating coupling can also be achieved by series
capacitance, the same or higher efficiency can be achieved through capacitance resonant
coupling.

Our project directly addresses the real-life challenges faced by industrial workers,
including fatigue, production delays, and material handling risks. By integrating a
Hydraulic Lift assist system into our specialized electric wagon, we're tackling these
challenges head-on.
Firstly, fatigue among workers is a significant concern, often resulting from the
repetitive manual lifting and transporting of heavy loads. Our wagon's Hydraulic Lift
system significantly reduces the physical strain involved in these tasks, minimizing
fatigue and the associated health risks for workers. In our rigorous testing, we observed
that our Hydraulic Electric Trolley demonstrated superior load-carrying capacity
compared to manual trolleys, with trials consistently showcasing its ability to handle
heavier loads efficiently. For instance, while manual trolleys typically carried loads
ranging from 150kg to 220kg, our Hydraulic Electric Trolley consistently managed
loads from 250kg to 270kg, thus reducing the need for manual labour and minimizing
worker fatigue.
Secondly, production delays can occur due to inefficiencies in material handling
processes. Our wagon streamlines these processes by providing a reliable and efficient
means of transporting heavy loads within industrial environments. Through meticulous
testing, we determined that our Hydraulic Electric Trolley exhibited faster travel speeds
and shorter cycle times per batch compared to manual trolleys. For instance, our trolley
achieved speeds ranging from 2.28 m/s to 2.46 m/s, while manual trolleys typically
operated at speeds between 0.8 m/s to 1.2 m/s. Additionally, our trolley demonstrated
an increased capacity to transfer batches of components within a work period, as
evidenced by the higher number of batches transferred compared to manual trolleys.
Lastly, material handling risks, such as injuries from lifting heavy objects or accidents
during transportation, pose significant hazards to workers' safety. By implementing our
wagon with a Hydraulic Lift system, we're mitigating these risks by minimizing the
need for manual lifting and providing a secure means of transporting heavy loads.
Furthermore, our trolley incorporates safety features such as scissor links to enhance
stability and prevent accidents during the lifting process.
In summary, our project not only addresses the immediate challenges faced by
industrial workers but also offers long-term solutions that prioritize their health, safety,
and overall well-being. By providing a safer and more efficient alternative to manual
material handling, our specialized electric wagon contributes to a more productive and
sustainable working environment.

ProjectTitle: ARDUINO-ENHANCED MASSAGING SEAT COVER FOR DRIVER COMFORT AND HAPTIC ALERTNESS

    SAMINENI VAMSI KRISHNA	  (21075A2411)
    YADA VIJAY RAMARAO	  (21075A2413)
AdditionalInfo.Abtract:
Sedentary behaviors have become a common problem in modern culture, causing discomfort, muscle cramps, and poor blood circulation, especially during activities such as driving. Recognizing these difficulties, this project investigates the feasibility of incorporating massage capabilities into driver seats via the unique usage of seat covers. Unlike standard massaging seats, which are typically expensive and difficult to install into older vehicles due to their complicated built-in mechanics, this project presents a cost-effective and customizable alternative that uses unique seat cover designs with built-in massage elements. The anticipated seat coverings are rigorously made using material studies, ergonomic design principles, and engineering concepts.By precisely arranging several nodes within the seat cover, drivers can target specific areas of the vertebrae and muscles, creating a true and relaxing sensation. 
In addition, these massage elements promote blood flow to crucial areas including the lower back, upper back, and thighs, promoting relaxation, lowering fatigue, and relieving muscle cramps on lengthy journeys. Vibration motors built within the seat covers are essential to their performance. Eccentric rotating mass (ERM) vibration motors are used, which comprise of an electric motor shaft and a tiny, unbalanced mass. As the motor rotates, the unequal distribution of mass causes mechanical oscillations, which produce the required vibration.Encasing these ERM motors in enclosed cups ensures that they operate efficiently, giving continuous and focused vibrations to users.
One of the primary benefits of this revolutionary technology is its versatility and usability. The lightweight design of the seat coverings allows for quick installation and compatibility with a wide range of vehicle seat models. Also, users can modify the vibratory frequency and target certain areas of the body to personalize their massage experience.

AdditionalInfo.Abtract:
Aluminum-based metal matrix composites with single or multiple reinforcements exhibit improved mechanical properties, such as higher strength, stiffness, and wear resistance. AMMCs are finding applications in the aerospace and automobile industries.
AA6061 MMC composites were successfully fabricated, through the liquid metallurgy route via the stir casting method, with the incorporation of Alumina nanoparticles at constant weight percentages along with different weight percentages of rice husk ash using a stir casting process with ultrasonication. 
The formed composites have been thoroughly studied for microstructure refinement, nano-particulate distribution, and bonding with the matrix by using optical microscopy In addition, the composites were analysed for density, porosity, and elemental composition.
 Further, the composites were tested for the investigation of mechanical properties, like micro-hardness and tensile strength, to investigate the influence of ultrasonic vibration on the arrangement of Alumina nano-particulates and Rice husk ash.

AdditionalInfo.Abtract: A fuel cell is similar to a battery in that it produces energy continuously while operating at high efficiency by converting fuel (typically hydrogen) and an oxidizing agent (commonly oxygen) into electricity via.
